{{BookCat}}

A '''software design pattern''' is a general reusable solution to a problem that repeats itself in [[w:software design|software design]] within a given context. It is not a finished design that can be transformed directly into code, and constitutes a description or template for a problem that can be used in many different situations. Software design patterns are formalized best practices that have to be implemented in applications.<ref>[http://static.springsource.org/spring/docs/3.1.x/spring-framework-reference/html/overview.html 1. Introduction to Spring Framework]</ref> A part of the software design patterns are [[w:Object-oriented programming|object-oriented]] design patterns that show relationships and [[w:interaction|interaction]]s between [[w:class (computer science)|class]]es or [[w:object (computer science)|object]]s without specifying the final application objects that are involved. Patterns that imply [[w:Object-oriented programming|object-orientation]] or more generally mutable state, are not as applicable in [[w:functional programming|functional programming]] languages.
Software design patterns reside in the domain of modules and interconnections. At a higher level there are [[w:Architectural pattern (computer science)|architectural patterns]] that are larger in scope. These usually describe an overall pattern followed by an entire system.<ref name = "R.C.Martin">{{cite web | url = http://www.objectmentor.com/resources/articles/Principles_and_Patterns.pdf | title = Design Principles and Design Patterns | last = Martin | first = Robert C. | authorlink = Robert C. Martin | accessdate = 2000}}</ref>
Important design pattern types are * '''[[w:Behavioural patterns|Behavioural patterns]]''' * '''[[w:Concurrency patterns|Concurrency patterns]]''' * '''[[w:Creational patterns|Creational patterns]]''' * '''[[w:Structural patterns|Structural patterns]]'''
== See also == * [[Introduction to Software Engineering/Architecture/Design Patterns|Design Patterns in Software Engineering]]
== References== {{Reflist|2}} {{Wikipedia|Software design pattern}}
{{BookCat}}

